From the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.techcentralstation.com/1051/defensewrapper.jsp?PID=1051-350&amp;CID=1051-022602B">article</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->:<br>
<br>
 Opponents have tended to focus - ludicrously - not only on the technology's safety but also on its supposed military implications. Bruce Gagnon of the Florida-based Global Network Against Weapons and Nuclear Power in Space, told the Los Angeles Times this month: &quot;It's our position that just like missile defense is a Trojan horse for the Pentagon's real agenda for domination of space, NASA's nuclear rocket is a Trojan horse for militarization of space.&quot; During the anti-Cassini campaign, physicist Michio Kaku warned that the Saturn probe was a step toward &quot;nuclear-powered battle stations in outer space.&quot; <br>
<br>
In reality, the main thrust of space nuclear technology is its ability to operate far from both Earth and the sun. Cassini's generators produce only 800 watts of electricity - less than what's used by a dozen light bulbs - but will do so over a 12-year mission in deep space. Nuclear rockets, once they are developed, would only marginally cut down on flight time to, say, Baghdad, but are enormously helpful if one is traveling to Pluto. If the military is behind NASA's nuclear initiative, then the enemy must be extraterrestrial. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MegaLipidCephaloid</span><br>  Posts: 353<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/1/02 5:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=75.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The &quot;Trojan horse&quot; argument</span><hr size=1> The article was much too broadbrush.<br>
<br>
The Trojan Horse argument is not so much nuclear rockets, as nuclear reactors.  <br>
I have (after seeing him swiped at a zillion time here) read some of his stuff. He's not particulally technical and seems rather single-minded. It was interesting that he makes a distinction between &quot;militarizing&quot; space and &quot;weaponizing&quot; space.  &quot;Militarizing&quot; includes spy satellites, military communications, command and control, etc. He appears to accept that role. &quot;Weaponizing&quot; is just that.. machines used for destruction. He appears to see space reactors as powerful energy sources usable for various beam weapons or kinetic projectile launchers. The reactors being contemplated are designs specifically created by and for the military. <br>
Whether you agree or not with the likelihood,  the dual-use -potential- is real.<br>
<br>
I personally don't think the military at this time is particularly interested and thus I disagree with Gagnon (at least for the short-term). The military has stated publicly that they are more then satisfied with solar and chemical powered devices.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
<br>
BTW - It is important to note that the 1 in a million chance was not that the RTG would survive a swingby re-entry (becuase they are not so designed), it was their estimate of not having a situation where the ship deviated (by mechanical malfunction or miscalculation) by 700 miles after a trip of billions of miles. The 1 in a million was made by piling assumptions.  I personally thought there was not much risk (altho I sure wouldn't like to quantify the risk - you never know when someone may mix English with metric numbers... Naw, can't happen..) <br>
Some people simply were not willing to accept the POTENTIAL for 70 pounds of Pu238 (equal to the entire release of all the above ground nuclear testing) to vaporize into the biosphere.<br>
That does not make them ignorant fear-mongers. They simply have different acceptances of the risks.<br>
<br>
